05639nam a22008895i 9783110636000DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022930263  a97831106360007 a10.1515/97831106360002doi  a(DE-B1597)506940  a(OCoLC)1298722866  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0370302bisacsh00aRethinking Period Boundaries :bNew Approaches to Continuity and Discontinuity in Modern European History and Culture /ced. by Lucian George, Jade McGlynn. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (V, 258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeriodization is an ever-present feature of the grammar of history-writing. As with all grammatical rules, the order it imposes can structure but also stifle historical interpretations. Though few historians consider their period boundaries as anything more than useful guidelines, heuristic artifice all too easily congeals into immovable structure, blinkering the historical gaze. In this cross-disciplinary volume, an international group of historians and cultural scholars considers different ways in which accepted period boundaries in modern European history and cultural studies can be challenged and rethought. Alongside a theoretical introduction and epilogue, the volume contains seven case studies exploring hitherto under-researched continuities and discontinuities in the social, cultural, intellectual, literary, labour and art history of 19th- and 20th-century Europe, with a particular focus on the continent’s East. Topics covered include French anti-communism, peasant memories of serfdom, cosmopolitan art in a nationalist age, the communist takeover of Poland, Russian literary history, and national day traditions in East-Central Europe. To problematize period boundaries, the chapters in this volume adopt the perspective of social groups that standard periodization schemes have ignored; shine a light on "awkward" actors who have appeared out of step with canonical understandings of their period; consider how historical actors themselves divide up history and how this informs historical practice; and explore the difficulties that the non-synchronicity of different historical processes can pose for periodization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aEuropäische Geschichte. 4aModerne. 4aPeriodisierung. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean history.  amodern history.  aperiodization.1 aBenedetti, Alessia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurek, Jan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClift, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Lucian , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeorge, Lucian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLokhmatov, Aleksei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGlynn, Jade, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobertson, Ritchie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSecklehner, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalabér, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 En